nivore Conservation argues that conserving and coexisting with large carnivores is as much a problem of people and governance—of reconciling diverse and sometimes conflicting values, perspectives, and organizations, and of effective decision making in the public sphere—as it is a problem of animal ecology and behavior. By adopting an integrative approach, editors Susan G. Clark and Murray B. Rutherford seek to examine and understand the interrelated development of conservation science, law, and policy, as well as how these forces play out in courts, other public institutions, and the field. In combining real-world examples with discussions of conservation and policy theory, Large Carnivore Conservation not only explains how traditional management approaches have failed to meet the needs of all parties, but also highlights examples of innovative, successful strategies and provides practical recommendations for improving future conservation efforts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCarnivoraxConservationzNorth America. 0aGrizzly bearxConservationzNorth America. 0aHuman-animal relationshipszNorth America. 0aPumaxConservationzNorth America. 0aTop predatorsxConservationzNorth America. 0aWildlife conservationzNorth America. 0aWildlife managementzNorth America. 0aWolves - Conservation - North America. 0aWolvesxConservationzNorth America. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aconservation, animals, wildlife, environmentalism, carnivores, predators, wolf, grizzly bear, mountain lion, yukon, arizona, american west, populations, ecology, animal behavior, puma, governance, legal system, government, management, wyoming, hunting, ranching, kluane region, science, alberta, central rockies, mountains, nonfiction, blackfoot watershed, montana, banff national park.1 aAnderson, Avery C., econtributor.4ctb4ht